---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<Base
  title="MSc thesis — Tom Scholtes"
  description="Augmented gravity model: Institutions, Infrastructure and Globalization impact on bilateral exports among OECD countries. MSc Economics & Business, Erasmus University Rotterdam, 2020."
  path="/thesis"
>
  <Nav active="thesis" />
  <main>
    <section>
      <div class="container">
        <article class="prose">
          <div class="meta">MSc thesis · Erasmus University Rotterdam · 2020</div>
          <h1>Augmented gravity model</h1>
          <p style="font-size:20px; color:var(--ink)">
            Institutions, infrastructure and globalization impact on bilateral exports
            among OECD countries.
          </p>

          <h2>Abstract</h2>
          <p>
            The classical gravity model of international trade explains bilateral export
            volumes as a function of economic mass and geographic distance. This thesis
            augments the canonical specification with measures of institutional quality
            (rule of law, regulatory quality), infrastructure capacity (logistics
            performance, ICT readiness), and globalization intensity (KOF index) across
            OECD bilateral pairs.
          </p>
          <p>
            Panel-data regressions over 2000–2018 confirm the robustness of the gravity
            core while showing significant marginal explanatory power for the augmented
            variables — particularly institutional quality on the exporter side and
            infrastructure on the importer side.
          </p>

          <h2>Method</h2>
          <p>
            PPML (Poisson Pseudo Maximum Likelihood) estimation, country-pair fixed
            effects, year fixed effects, multilateral resistance terms via remoteness
            indices. Heteroskedasticity-robust standard errors clustered at the
            country-pair level.
          </p>

          <h2>Findings</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>A one-standard-deviation increase in exporter rule-of-law correlates with a 4–7% increase in bilateral exports, holding gravity terms constant.</li>
            <li>Importer logistics performance has roughly twice the marginal effect of importer GDP per capita on bilateral imports.</li>
            <li>KOF globalization is significant in the cross-section but absorbed by country-pair fixed effects in the panel.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Limitations</h2>
          <p>
            OECD-only sample biases results toward high-income trade patterns; institutional
            and infrastructure variables are highly collinear with GDP per capita; the
            sample period predates the COVID-19 trade dislocation.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-top:48px">
            <a href="/">← Back to home</a>
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>
